          <td style="padding:0.75rem;border:1px solid var(--md-sys-color-outline)">$0</td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-bottom:2rem">
      <h2>Case Study: Mekong MCU System</h2>
      <p>Mekong CLI uses MCU (Mekong Credit Units) as its billing primitive. Each MCU maps to one AI-powered task delivered successfully. Simple read operations cost 0 MCU. Complex multi-step analyses like annual strategy documents cost 5 MCU.</p>
      <p>Critical design choice: <strong>deduct only on successful delivery</strong>. If the agent fails, the customer pays nothing. This aligns incentives perfectly — Mekong is motivated to deliver quality results because revenue depends on it.</p>
      <p>The HTTP 402 response on zero balance prevents partial execution entirely. Customers who hit the limit get a clear signal to upgrade or purchase additional credits — not a degraded partial experience.</p>
    </section>

    <section style="margin-bottom:2rem">
      <h2>Conversion Optimization for Credit-Based Products</h2>
      <p>Credit-based pricing requires different conversion tactics than flat-rate subscriptions:</p>
      <ul style="color:var(--md-sys-color-on-surface);line-height:1.8">
        <li><strong>Free credits on signup:</strong> Give enough to experience real value, not just a demo. 20-50 credits is the typical range.</li>
        <li><strong>Low-balance notifications at 20%:</strong> Prompt upgrade before the user hits zero and churns out of frustration.</li>
        <li><strong>Usage-based upsell triggers:</strong> Users who consistently hit 80%+ of their monthly allocation are prime upgrade candidates.</li>
        <li><strong>Annual pre-purchase discount:</strong> 20% off annual credits vs monthly drives cash flow and reduces churn.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

